Because the tar.gz file contains an un-named folder "." the tar type extractor is not able to extract the contents of the folder. If the folder is named there is no problem.

<details><summary>File: composer.json</summary>

```json
    "require": {
        "ec-europa/platform_dev": "~2.4.0"
    },
    "repositories": [
        {
            "type": "package",
            "package": {
                "name": "ec-europa/platform_dev",
                "version": "2.4.63",
                "type": "drupal-core",
                "dist": {
                    "url": "https://github.com/ec-europa/platform-dev/releases/download/2.4.63/platform-dev-2.4.63.tar.gz",
                    "type": "tar"
                }
            }
        }
    ]
}
```

</details>

<details><p><summary>Run: composer install</summary>

```
  [PharException]
  Extraction from phar "/home/verbral/platform-composer/build/28911af645fcdc4a61e64f6ef3e444ab.gz" failed: Cannot extract ".", internal error
```
</details></p>

I know this is an edge case. But would it be possible to allow for un-named folders to be extracted? I'm not really in the mood to re-upload 500 packages to our repository.

Possible solution provided on PHP documentation page:
http://php.net/manual/en/phardata.extractto.php

Hello!

I want to discuss if we can add support for optional dependencies to composer.

Problem explained by the LiipImagineBundle:
The LiipImagineBundle:2.0 had an dependency to PHP-CS-FIXER
```json
{
  "require-dev": {
    "friendsofphp/php-cs-fixer": "^1.0|^2.0"
  }
}
```
and PHP-CS-Fixer doesn't support PHP 7.3 see https://github.com/FriendsOfPHP/PHP-CS-Fixer/blob/2.9/composer.json
```json
{
  "require": {
        "php": "^5.6 || >=7.0 <7.3"
  }
}
```
See discussion https://github.com/FriendsOfPHP/PHP-CS-Fixer/issues/3323 - PHP-CS-FIXER will not support PHP 7.3 at the moment. So the nightly php travis builds fail because composer could not resolve the dependencies. LiipImagineBundle now removed PHP-CS-FIXER dependency
 at the moment.

How can we solve the problem in composer?

One solution will be to add support for optional requirements which can be installed or skipped.
What do you think about this?

Related Issues (I found)
- #6321 use case for conflict

Possible syntax
```json
{
  "optional": {
    "friendsofphp/php-cs-fixer": "^1.0|^2.0"
  }, 
  "optional-dev": {
    "friendsofphp/php-cs-fixer": "^1.0|^2.0"
  }
}
```
or question mark before
```json
{
  "require-dev": {
    "?friendsofphp/php-cs-fixer": "^1.0|^2.0"
  }
}
```
or dash for skipped
```json
{
  "require-dev": {
    "friendsofphp/php-cs-fixer": "^1.0|^2.0|-"
  }
}
```


Thank you very much

issue_comments.body:
The following form work fine now (handled by `GitDriver`):

```
"repositories": [
    {
        "type": "vcs",
        "url": "git@bitbucket.org:vendor/repo.git"
    }
]
```

Private repos specified as `https://bitbucket.org/vendor/repo.git` or `https://vendor@bitbucket.org/vendor/repo.git` does not work.

@mvriel or what about a type called 'require-extra' which is defined by `vendor => array(version, path)`

e.g.

```
    "require-extra": {
        "foo/bar": ["1.2.3", "vendor-dir"],
    }, 
```

This way it can truly work for anything.  There are other usecases for example system modules e.g. in Zikula or Drupal where modules sort of need to go in a special folder.

