This isn't entirely true, the following outputs ö and then garbage (if saved/served as UTF8).

```
echo utf8_encode(strtolower(utf8_decode('Ö')));
echo strtolower('Ö');
```

All I want to make sure of is that the package names are case insensitive. I lowercase them when they're output in packagist, and I thought lowercasing the user input in composer would complete the loop. Now if we say we only support [a-z0-9_-] in package names, fine by me, but we need to make this explicit and not allow stuff to be mangled if it contains accented chars.

Sorry to insist, but I'm not seeing the same here:

```
echo ord(utf8_encode(strtolower(utf8_decode('Ö'))));
echo ord(strtolower('Ö'));
echo ord(utf8_encode(mb_strtolower(utf8_decode('Ö'), 'ISO-8859-1')));
echo ord(mb_strtolower('Ö', 'UTF-8'));
```

Prints 195 227 195 195
Printing the second byte of each gets you: 182 150 182 182

It seems to me that strtolower() with UTF8 input is touching things that go beyond the scope of ASCII chars, and therefore should not be relied upon since we do have UTF8.

